explanation:
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit: needed to know all possible return values and side effects (e.g. whether it can always fail or always succeed, whether it modifies/validates token). These determine reachability of the following code.
- OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex: needed to know when it returns OS_SUCCESS vs other codes (i.e. whether the inner block that assigns token->obj_idx/obj_id and calls ConvertToken can ever be reached).
- OS_ObjectIdConvertToken: needed to know its possible return values and whether it always/never returns (or long-jumps), and what it does to global lock state; its return controls whether TransactionCancel is invoked and whether the final return follows the success path.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel: needed to know whether it can alter control flow (e.g. long-jump, abort) or always returns normally; determines whether the cleanup branch represents reachable code.
- OS_SUCCESS: the canonical success return value used in the comparisons; needed to interpret the numeric return codes from the called routines and thereby determine which branches are reachable.
- OS_object_token_t: definition (fields obj_idx, obj_id and any invariants) required to understand whether writes to token fields are meaningful and whether token must be non-NULL (preconditions) — affects whether certain statements are effectively unreachable.
- OS_lock_mode_t, osal_objtype_t, osal_id_t: the parameter types and any semantic constraints (e.g. valid ranges) can affect whether OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit/OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex can succeed; needed to reason about possible execution paths.

These symbols provide the prototypes, return-value semantics and type/precondition information necessary to determine if any branches or statements in OS_ObjectIdGetById can never be executed (i.e., are unreachable).
